      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Accelerationists and critics argue that instrumental convergence is an oversimplification of complex, emergent systems, not a deterministic law of physics. They contend that current AI architectures lack the necessary general world model or intentionality for such monolithic goal-seeking behavior to manifest reliably. Furthermore, they counter the scaling argument by pointing to diminishing returns and the practical, engineering hurdles—like energy consumption or data quality—that will inevitably slow down the exponential curve. Their position is that we are vastly overestimating the current trajectory of AI capabilities.",
      "source": "target",
